sibility of women, but also reveals the complex processes that led to women's relatively swift exit from most public institutions in the early 1800s. As artists, writers, and reformers, Spanish women took up pens, joined academies and economic societies, formed tertulias—similar to French salons—and became active in the burgeoning public discourse of Enlightenment. In analyzing the meaning of women's presence in diverse centers of Enlightenment, Smith offers a new interpretation of the dynamics among political discourse, social action, and gender ideologies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFeminismzSpainxHistoryy18th century. 0aSex rolezSpainxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomenzSpainxHistoryy18th century. 0aWomenzSpainxIntellectual life. 0aWomenzSpainxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aenlightenment.  aeurope.  afemale artist.  afemale author.  afemale citizen.  afemininity.  afeminism.  agender roles.  agender studies.  agender.  ahistory.  aintellectual women.  anonfiction.  apolitical discourse.  apolitical reform.  apolitics.  apublic discourse.  asocial action.  aspanish women.  atertulias.  athe woman question.  awomen in history.  awomen.  awomens place.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024583940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093222740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520932227423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520932227/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY